<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900904-0082</DOCNO><DOCID>900904-0082.</DOCID><HL>   Arguments Open in Trial   Of Hong Kong's Ronald Li</HL><DATE>09/04/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   FREST H.CPA</CO><IN>STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><LP>   HONG KONG -- Opening arguments began Monday in the closelywatched corruption trial of former Hong Kong Stock Exchangechairman Ronald Li, which prosecutors expect to last sixweeks.   Mr. Li, 61 years old, pleaded innocent last week to twocounts of accepting preferential offerings of shares inCathay Pacific Airways Ltd., and Novel Enterprises Ltd. in1986 and 1987, in exchange for helping to obtain listings forthe companies' shares.</LP><TEXT>   The former official, who is free on HK$12 million bail(US$1.6 million), faces a maximum penalty of seven years inprison and HK$500,000 in fines on each count.   Mr. Li and six other former bourse officials, includinghis son Alfred, will be jointly tried in February on sixsimilar corruption charges. A string of other counts weredismissed in separate actions earlier this year.</TEXT></DOC>